{"id":"d=origam-topic-3912//p=67f647a5384542cb94913967c9e49dd0","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-3912"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["5a00da1b464c41bc9f18c11b85f3a52f"],"__file_part":["334b1cdec28a47818d89f11e1a0150c5"],"__part_n":["1"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["3912"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-run-origam-server/3912"],"title":["How to run ORIGAM Server"],"imagesFound":["5"],"imagesDescribed":["5"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7605661211bed480b465b8b8647607f85d484aeb.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/338aaa4300f405cdb24aad70f85e1df409201d04.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/eda5f27155b3eb6446cb4c0b67fa7bfe641ebd86.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7db1bdb1af5e071e0e16965338d08063eaa37b04.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4b9a1f2c847171eb35f23651e8de7eaa8d7ee961.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" in your project and run the CMD file typing, for example: \n  myapplication_Linux.cmd\n  \n \n    MacOS users need to convert the file to a Shell Script and run it in Mac Terminal or create a Docker container with a Windows image using a virtual machine to run the script. \n \n If everything runs in order, at the end of all the generated code, you will get a notification that your Docker container ( Application ) is started. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/338aaa4300f405cdb24aad70f85e1df409201d04.png]\nDescription: The image displays a Command Prompt window titled \u0022myapplic.\u0022 It shows a series of error messages and warnings related to a .NET application. The logs indicate an issue with the Origam.WorkFlow.WorkQueueService, specifically methods such as GetQueues and WorkQueueAutoProcessTimerElapsed. It contains a warning about the lack of XML encryption for data protection, indicating a key that may be stored in unencrypted form. The hosting environment is labeled as \u0022Production,\u0022 with the content root path specified as \u0022/home/origam/HTML5.\u0022 The application is listening on the address \u0022http://[::]:8080,\u0022 and it notes that pressing Ctrl\u002BC will shut down the application.\n\n\n  \n You will also see your container running in Docker: \n \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/eda5f27155b3eb6446cb4c0b67fa7bfe641ebd86.png]\nDescription: The image displays the Docker Desktop application interface, specifically the \u0022Containers\u0022 section. It includes the header \u0022Containers\u0022 with a sub-label for providing feedback. The container CPU usage is indicated as \u00222.00% / 1200% (12 CPUs available)\u0022 and the container memory usage shows \u00221.58GB / 14.93GB.\u0022 The interface features a search bar, a toggle for \u0022Only show running containers,\u0022 and a table listing two containers: \u0022mssql2022\u0022 with ID \u0022338f018bc307\u0022 using \u00228.29%\u0022 CPU and \u0022myapplication\u0022 with ID \u0022cb16eba39880\u0022 using \u00220.14%\u0022 CPU. Each entry has associated columns for container ID, image type, port mapping, and action buttons.\n\n\n  \n   Troubleshooting \n In case there is any issue, you need to fix that and run the script again. \n Here, for example, is how it looks when you run the Docker script without running the DB server: \n \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7db1bdb1af5e071e0e16965338d08063eaa37b04.png]\nDescription: The image displays a Command Prompt window showing an error message related to a .NET application running on ASP.NET Core. The visible text includes a critical error related to application startup: \u0022Microsoft.AspNetCore.Hosting.Diagnostics[6]\u0022. The specific error details state: \u0022System.Data.SqlClient.SqlException (0x80131904): A network-related or instance-specific error occurred while establishing a connection to SQL Server. The server was not found or was not accessible. Verify that the instance name is correct and that SQL Server is configured to allow remote connections (provider: TCP Provider, error: 40 \u2013 Could not open a connection to SQL Server).\u0022 The stack trace follows, indicating where the error originated within the application code. This information suggests that the application is failing to connect to a SQL Server database, likely due to configuration issues.\n\n\n  \n The container will be created in Docker despite this error, but if you run it, it will crash after a while, and you will see the same error in the log: \n \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4b9a1f2c847171eb35f23651e8de7eaa8d7ee961.png]\nDescription: The interface displayed is the Docker Desktop application, specifically the \u0022Containers\u0022 section for an application named \u0022myapplication\u0022. The logs section shows a series of timestamped log entries from January 20, 2025, at 15:00:58. Highlighted in red is a critical error message indicating an application startup exception relating to a SQL Server connection failure. The error details state: \u0022A network-related or instance-specific error occurred while establishing a connection to SQL Server. The server was not found or was not accessible. Verify that the instance name is correct and that SQL Server is configured to allow remote connections. (provider: TCP Provider, error: 40 - Could not open a connection to SQL Server)\u0022. The interface includes buttons for status management and displays engine statistics such as RAM and disk usage.\n\n\n","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:39:30"},"vector":[-0.013179617,-0.0006453296,-0.0793713,0.0047453954,-0.04388635,-0.01817348,-0.033456203,-0.0032587678,-0